\citation{li2025stppo}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.12}{\ignorespaces Outcome supervision vs process supervision for reasoning tasks. \textbf  {Left:} Outcome-only rewards evaluate the final answer, potentially rewarding flawed reasoning that happens to land on the right conclusion. \textbf  {Right:} Process supervision gives step-level feedback, validating every step of the reasoning process. Research has shown that step-level reward models typically exceed the performance of outcome-based models on MATH, with the gap widening as sampling budgets increase---sound reasoning chains generalize better to new problems. }}{53}{figure.caption.96}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:process_supervision}{{3.12}{53}{Outcome supervision vs process supervision for reasoning tasks. \textbf {Left:} Outcome-only rewards evaluate the final answer, potentially rewarding flawed reasoning that happens to land on the right conclusion. \textbf {Right:} Process supervision gives step-level feedback, validating every step of the reasoning process. Research has shown that step-level reward models typically exceed the performance of outcome-based models on MATH, with the gap widening as sampling budgets increase---sound reasoning chains generalize better to new problems}{figure.caption.96}{}}
